[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(10) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And let these also first be proved.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—No formal investigation, either in public before the congregation, or in private before Timothy and his fellow presbyters, is here referred to. What is most probably the meaning of the word is—the deacon should for a time perform many of the various duties on probation, to test his fitness before he was formally set apart for the holy office. So much of the work belonging to these officials of the early Church necessarily partook of a partially secular character, that such a trial of their fitness could well be made.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Then let them use the office of a deacon.—Better rendered, let them serve as deacons, if, after the trial, inquiry, and period of probation, they be found blameless.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Then let them use the office of a deacon.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better rendered, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "let them serve as deacons, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "if, after the trial, inquiry, and period of probation, they be found blameless.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Timothy 3:10. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Timothy 3:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Let these also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— (The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "implies that the same rule was to be observed with relation to bishops) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "first be proved ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— “By the examination,” says Whitby, “of the soundness of their faith, and the purity of their former lives: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and then let them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "be admitted to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "use the office of a deacon, being ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "thus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "found blameless.” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And he shows, by a quotation from the Life of the Emperor Severus, written by Lampridius, and from the epistles of Cyprian, that such an examination was used at the ordination of both bishops and deacons in the churches of the early Christians, and that it was a practice derived from the apostles. Some, however, think that the apostle required, in this direction, that no one should be made either a bishop or a deacon, till he had given proof both of his steadfastness in the faith, and of his genuine piety and good conduct during a reasonable space of time after his conversion: or, that the persons admitted to these offices should be under trial for a while, how they conducted themselves therein, and then afterward, if they gave satisfaction, they should be confirmed in them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3:8-13 The deacons were at first appointed to distribute the charity of the church, and to manage its concerns, yet pastors and evangelists were among them. The deacons had a great trust reposed in them. They must be grave, serious, prudent men. It is not fit that public trusts should be lodged in the hands of any, till they are found fit for the business with which they are to be trusted. All who are related to ministers, must take great care to walk as becomes the gospel of Christ.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And let these also first be proved - That is, tried or tested in regard to the things which were the proper qualifications for the office. This does not mean that they were to be employed as \"preachers,\" but that they were to undergo a proper trial in regard to their fitness for the office which they were to fill. They were not to be put into it without any opportunity of knowing what they were. It should be ascertained that they were grave, serious, temperate, trustworthy men; men who were sound in the faith, and who would not dishonor the office. It is not said here that there should be a \"formal\" trial, as if they were candidates for this office; but the meaning is, that they should have had an opportunity of making their character known, and should have gained such respect for their piety, and their other qualifications, that there would be reason to believe that they would perform the functions of the office well. Thus, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 6:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", when deacons were first appointed, the church was directed to \"look out seven men of honest report,\" who might be appointed to the office.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Then let them use the office of a deacon - Let them be appointed to this office, and fulfil its duties.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Being found blameless - If nothing can be alleged against their character see the notes on 1 Timothy 3:2. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Being found blameless - If nothing can be alleged against their character see the notes on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Timothy 3:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "10. \"And moreover,\" &c. [Alford].",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "be proved—not by a period of probation, but by a searching inquiry, conducted by Timothy, the ordaining president (1Ti 5:22), whether they be \"blameless\"; then when found so, \"let them act as deacons.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "blameless—Greek, \"unexceptionable\"; as the result of public investigation unaccused [Tittmann].",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The higher officers ought to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "be proved, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "( as well as these of a lower order), as by examination or conference, so (which possibly is here more intended) by an observation of their lives and conversation, for some time before they were admitted into this employment. Then, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "being found blameless, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " they were to be admitted into this employment. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
